You can use [projection][1]:

    @Query(&quot;SELECT count(a.age) as age, count(w.weight) as weight from animals a inner join weight_table w on a.id = w.id&quot;)
    public List&lt;MyObject&gt; myMethodNameDescribingFunctionality();

where `MyObject` could be an interface:

    public interface MyObject {
        @Value(&quot;#{target.age}&quot;)
        int age();
        
        @Value(&quot;#{target.weight}&quot;)
        int weight;
    }


  [1]: https://www.baeldung.com/spring-data-jpa-projections

for using custom class I use first to create a constructor for these attributes  

    public class MyObject {
         private int age;
         private int weight;
         public  MyObject(int age , int weight) {
             this.age=age;
             this.weight = weight; 
         }
    }

after that, in hql u can call this constructor in the same order of values 

    @Query(&quot;SELECT new com.packagename.MyObject(count(a.age), count(w.weight)) from animals a inner join weight_table w on a.id = w.id&quot;)


you will return a list from MyObject objects

